This paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category as it deals with denoising autoencoders and their ability to learn invariant representations of natural images. Additionally, the paper discusses experiments using real-world images, which further supports the likelihood of it belonging to the cs.CV sub-category. 

The paper also involves machine learning (cs.LG) as it discusses the use of a denoising autoencoder and its ability to learn representations. 

Neural networks (cs.NE) is another likely sub-category as the paper discusses the structure of a denoising autoencoder and its connections between the encoder and decoder. 

Artificial intelligence (cs.AI) is also a possible sub-category as the paper discusses the ability of the denoising autoencoder to learn invariant representations, which is a key aspect of artificial intelligence. 

Finally, natural language processing (cs.CL) is a less likely sub-category as the paper does not directly deal with language processing, but it does involve the use of autoencoders, which can be used in natural language processing tasks.
